'''Arthur J. "Jerry" Kremer''' (born May 27, 1935) is an attorney, author and political consultant. He served in the New York State Assembly for 13 terms from 1966 until 1988. He founded Empire Government Strategies, where he currently serves as Chairman.<ref>[http://empiregs.com/arthur-jerry-kremer/ "Arthur “Jerry” Kremer"]. ''Empire''.</ref> He is of-counsel to Ruskin Moscou Faltischek P.C., a Long Island law firm. He was recently voted to City and State NY's Power 100-Albany 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Power 100- Albany 2014|url=http://www.cityandstateny.com/2/92/power-100/power100-albany2014.html#.U-uL_vldVe9|website=City & State|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref>

== Early life ==

Kremer was born in Bronx, New York. He graduated from Franklin K. Lane High School in Queens, NY. He attended New York University and has a J.D. from Brooklyn Law School.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alumni|url=http://www.brooklaw.edu/alumniandfriends/getinvolved/officersanddirectors.aspx|website=Brooklyn Law School|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref>

He is married to the former Suzan Rosenholtz with whom he has two daughters, Katherine and Lindsay.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}} He was also married to Barbara Schatz, who died while Kremer was serving in the state legislature, and they had two daughters, Nora Lynn and Robin Malamud.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}} He has six grandchildren, Benjamin, Samuel, Brett, Gabrielle, Jenna, and Zachary.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}

== Political career ==

Kremer was a member of the [[New York State Assembly]], representing a district which includes the Five Towns, Long Beach, and other South Shore communities,<ref>[http://archive.longislandpress.com/2009/04/16/power-list-2009-hall-of-fame/ "Power List 2009 Hall of Fame"]. ''Long Island Press''.</ref> from 1966 to 1988, sitting in the [[176th New York State Legislature|176th]], [[177th New York State Legislature|177th]], [[178th New York State Legislature|178th]], [[179th New York State Legislature|179th]], [[180th New York State Legislature|180th]], [[181st New York State Legislature|181st]], [[182nd New York State Legislature|182nd]], [[183rd New York State Legislature|183rd]], [[184th New York State Legislature|184th]], [[185th New York State Legislature|185th]], [[186th New York State Legislature|186th]] and [[187th New York State Legislature]]s.

He served as Chair of the Assembly Energy Committee and helped write the original power plant siting law.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}} He then moved to the Ways and Means Committee which he chaired for 10 years.<ref>{{cite book|title=New York Magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1tcCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA14|date=4 December 1978|pages=14–}}</ref><ref name="LLC1985">{{cite book|author=New York Media, LLC|title=New York Magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZckBAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA9|date=7 October 1985|publisher=New York Media, LLC|pages=9–|issn=0028-7369}}</ref> During his tenure he focused his efforts on increasing the budget making powers of the legislature.<ref>LIBN Staff. [http://libn.com/2001/03/02/the-quotwhos-whoquot-list/ "The "Who's Who" List"]. ''Long Island Business News''.</ref>

Late in 1986, he was a candidate for [[Speaker of the New York State Assembly]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Lynn|first=Frank|title=Kremer in Race for Speaker|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/11/23/nyregion/kremer-in-race-for-speaker.html|work=[[New York Times]]|date=November 23, 1986|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> but [[Mel Miller]] was chosen instead. At the beginning of the session of 1987, Miller appointed [[Saul Weprin]] to replace Kremer as chair of the Ways and Means Committee.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kolbert|first=Elizabeth|title=Deposed Panel Chief Assails Speaker of Assembly|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/01/09/nyregion/deposed-panel-chief-assails-speaker-of-assembly.html|work=[[New York Times]]|date=January 9, 1987|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> In November 1988, Kremer was re-elected but, on December 14, he resigned his Assembly seat.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lynn|first=Frank|title=After Fall From Power, an Assemblyman Resigns|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/12/15/nyregion/after-fall-from-power-an-assemblyman-resigns.html|work=[[New York Times]]|date=December 15, 1988|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref>

===Legislation===

Kremer helped draft the New York "Shield Law", which allowed journalists to refuse or reveal the sources of the information in news articles.<ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/us/2013/11/12/new-york-court-asked-to-safeguard-journalists-right-to-protect-sources/ "New York court asked to safeguard journalists' right to protect sources"]. ''Fox News''.</ref>

Kremer sponsored the "[[Lemon law|Lemon Law]]", designed to protect consumers who find that they have purchased a defective automobile.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gargan|first=Edward A.|title='Lemon Law' Takes Effect Amid Disputes on Coverage|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/09/01/nyregion/lemon-law-takes-effect-amid-disputes-on-coverage.html|work=New York Times|date=September 1, 1983|access-date=March 4, 2019}}</ref>

Kremer lobbied for the reinstatement of the Article X Power Plant Siting Law.<ref>[http://www.electricityforum.com/news/nov07/NewYorkneedsmorepower.html "New York needs power plants"]. ''Knight-Ridder Tribune'', as posted at electricityforum.com .</ref>  In 2012, the legislation was renewed and Kremer was an advisor.>

During his term in office, Kremer also spoke and wrote on the subjects of Truth in Lending for banks, assistance to senior Citizens including a law mandating that seniors be notified of their eligibility for a tax break by local governments and the first state pharmaceutical distribution program, a law requiring that LIRR employees be trained in CPR, a law forcing gas distributors to disclose their records on all shipments and pay the corresponding tax, and price minimum on cigarettes to counteract bootlegging.

== Post assembly ==

In 2010, Kremer founded Empire Government Strategies, a government relations firm. He has served as government relations representation to Canon U.S.A., DMJM+Harris Engineering, the New York State Bowling Proprietor's Association, the Bus Association of New York State, Public Service Electric and Gas, Caithness Energy, MedReview, the Fair Assessment Committee, the Town of North Hempstead, and the New York Association of Wholesale Marketers.<ref>{{cite web|title=New York lobbyists|url=http://longisland.newsday.com/templates/simpleDB/?pid=353&brand=0&searchField=Lobbyist&q=empire+government+strategies|website=longisland.newsday.com|accessdate=16 October 2014}}</ref>

Kremer has spoken and written extensively about the energy industry and about energy policy in New York State and in the United States. He has testified on a number of occasions before the Nuclear Regulatory Commission. He is a supporter of the re-licensing of the Indian Point Energy nuclear power plant. He has served as Counsel to the Long Island Power Authority(LIPA) and Power Authority of New York State and has represented them in a number of cases before the New York Court of Appeals.

Kremer is a member of the Board of Trustees of Hofstra University<ref>{{cite web|title=Trustees of Hofstra University|url=http://www.hofstra.edu/About/Administration/President/pres_bot.html|website=Hofstra University|publisher=Hofstra University|accessdate=13 August 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808042852/http://www.hofstra.edu/about/Administration/President/pres_bot.html|archivedate=8 August 2014|df=}}</ref> and Chair Emeritus of the Young Peoples Chorus of New York City. He also serves as Vice Chairman of the Commission on Independent Colleges and Universities.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Board of Trustees|url=http://www.cicu.org/about/board-trustees/arthur-j-kremer|publisher=Commission on Independent Colleges and Universities|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> He is the Chairman of the New York Affordable Reliable Electricity Alliance<ref>http://www.bcnys.org/whatsnew/events/documents/2013/JerryKremer.pdf</ref> He is a Lt. Colonel (ret.) in the New York State Guard. He is a member of the State Commission on Professionalism in the Law by the appointment of the Chief Judge.

== Publications ==

<!-- Commented out because image was deleted: [[File:Winningalbany.JPG|thumb|Winning Albany by Jerry Kremer]] -->
In 2013, Kremer published his first book, ''Winning Albany, Untold Stories About the Famous and Not So Famous'', which recounts his experiences in state government.<ref>[http://www.longislandpress.com/2013/12/10/staff-picks-december-2013/ "Spencer's Pick: Winning Albany: Untold Stories About the Famous and Not So Famous by Jerry Kremer (New Idea Press)]. (book review) ''Long Island Press''.</ref><ref>http://www.brooklaw.edu/~/media/PDF/LawNotes/LawNotes_SP14_FULL_ISSUE.ashx</ref>
In addition to his 2013 book, he has written articles for the Huffington Post,<ref>{{cite news|title=Jerry Kremer|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jerry-kremer/|accessdate=13 August 2014|publisher=Huffington Post}}</ref> Long Island Business News, The Herald News] <ref>[http://liherald.com/search_mode/keyword/browse.html?search_filter=Jerry+Kremer "Keyword: Jerry Kremer - LIHerald.com - Nassau County's source for local news, breaking news, sports, entertainment & shopping"].</ref> and Politico.<ref>{{cite news|title=Arena Profile|url=http://www.politico.com/arena/bio/arthur_jerry_kremer.html|agency=8-12-14|publisher=Politico}}</ref> He has been the News12 political analyst for over fifteen years<ref>[http://rmfpc.com/arthur-jerry-kremer-to-serve-as-political-analyst-on-news12s-election-night-coverage-for-the-17th-year-2/ "Arthur “Jerry” Kremer to Serve as Political Analyst on News12’s Election Night Coverage for the 17th Year"]. ''RMFPC''.</ref> and appears regularly on the Fox network and ABC television.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}

